1. Requirement Document
1.1 Overview
A Go-based agent that monitors a web page for appointment availability (via AJAX requests) and can operate in two modes:

Alert Mode: detects availability, sends notifications with action buttons to book, but does not automatically book.

Booking Mode: automatically books an appointment based on configurable preferred days after detection.

The agent must mimic a real browser to evade WAF/bot detection, use lightweight HTTP clients, manage cookies/sessions per site, and be efficient with concurrency (max 2 threads per site). It should avoid duplicate notifications and duplicate booking attempts.

1.2 Functional Requirements
1.2.1 Mode Configuration
Configurable via config file (e.g., YAML) to switch between alert and booking mode.

Booking mode includes preferred days (e.g., ["Saturday", "Sunday"]) and optionally specific dates.

1.2.2 Availability Detection
Perform HTTP requests to a given AJAX endpoint that returns HTML containing availability information.

Parse HTML to extract available dates and corresponding booking links.

Must be able to handle multiple available dates.

Must be able to schedule checks at a specific "strike time" (e.g., 9:00 AM) with random jitter before the check (e.g., ±2 seconds) to mimic human behavior.

1.2.3 Notification (ntfy)
Send ntfy notifications to a configured topic when availability is found.

Notifications must include:

List of available dates.

For each date, a button linking directly to its booking page.

Buttons should be prioritized: weekends (Saturday, Sunday) first, then weekdays.

Clearly label weekend vs weekday buttons (e.g., "Weekend: Date").

1.2.4 Booking Automation
When in booking mode, after detecting availability:

Select the first preferred day (based on priority list) that is available.

Navigate to the booking link (may require login).

Handle login form (username/password) with proper session cookies.

Extract CSRF tokens or other hidden form fields from the page.

Submit the booking form with all required fields.

Parse the response to determine success or failure (based on HTML content or redirect).

Send a separate ntfy notification with the result.

1.2.5 Concurrency & State Management
Max 2 goroutines per site for concurrent availability checks (if multiple checks needed, e.g., polling).

Reuse a shared HTTP client per site with cookie jar and common headers.

Prevent duplicate availability notifications: track seen dates.

Prevent duplicate booking attempts: mark a day as "processing" while booking.

1.2.6 Stealth & Anti‑Detection
Use realistic browser headers (User-Agent, Accept-Language, etc.).

Add random delays between requests (jitter) to mimic human behavior.

Use TLS fingerprint mimicking (optional, but can use standard net/http with typical ciphers).

Rotate User-Agent only per session (not per request) to look consistent.

1.3 Non‑Functional Requirements
Performance: lightweight, fast, low memory footprint.

Modularity: components (scraper, booker, notifier, state) must be independent and replaceable.

Configurability: all site‑specific details (URLs, selectors, form fields) must be configurable without code changes.

Resilience: handle transient errors with retries, timeouts.

Logging: detailed logs for debugging.

1.4 Configuration Structure (Example)
yaml
site:
  name: "clinic"
  base_url: "https://example.com"
  availability_endpoint: "/api/availability"
  booking_link_selector: "a.booking-link"  # CSS selector for link extraction
  login_url: "https://example.com/login"
  login_form:
    username_field: "email"
    password_field: "password"
    submit_button: "submit"
    csrf_token_selector: "input[name='csrf_token']"
  booking_form:
    action_url: "https://example.com/book"
    fields:
      - name: "date"
        type: "hidden"
        value_selector: "input[name='date']"
      - name: "time"
        type: "select"
        options: "option[value]"
  success_indicator: "Congratulations"  # text on success page

mode: "alert"  # or "booking"
preferred_days: ["Saturday", "Sunday"]
strike_time: "09:00:00"
ntfy_topic: "myappointments"
max_workers: 2
request_jitter: "2s"
2. Architecture Design
2.1 High‑Level Components
text
┌─────────────┐      ┌──────────────┐      ┌─────────────┐
│   Config    │─────▶│  Scheduler   │─────▶│   Scraper   │
└─────────────┘      └──────────────┘      └──────┬──────┘
                                                   │
                                                   ▼
┌─────────────┐      ┌──────────────┐      ┌─────────────┐
│   Notifier  │◀─────│  State       │◀─────│   Parser    │
└─────────────┘      │  Manager     │      └─────────────┘
                     └──────┬───────┘
                            │
                            ▼
                     ┌──────────────┐
                     │   Booker     │
                     └──────────────┘
Config: loads configuration from file and environment.

Scheduler: runs at strike time with jitter, triggers availability check.

HTTP Client Manager: provides pre‑configured HTTP clients per site (cookie jar, headers, timeouts).

Scraper: performs requests, parses HTML using goquery.

Parser: extracts available dates and booking links.

State Manager: stores seen dates and booking status, ensures no duplicates.

Notifier: sends ntfy messages with buttons.

Booker: handles login and booking submission, uses shared HTTP client.

2.2 Concurrency Model
Use a worker pool (size = max_workers) per site to process availability checks.

Each check is a goroutine that acquires a token from a semaphore.

All checks for the same site reuse the same HTTP client (thread‑safe).

State management uses sync.Map or mutex‑protected maps.

2.3 Request Flow
Alert Mode
Scheduler triggers at strike time.

Scraper sends AJAX request → gets HTML.

Parser extracts dates & links.

For each new date, send ntfy notification with buttons (weekends prioritized).

Mark dates as seen.

Booking Mode
Scheduler triggers.

Scraper checks availability → returns dates & links.

For each preferred day (in order) that is available:

Check if already booked or processing (state).

If not, start booking:

Load login page (if needed) → extract CSRF token.

Post login credentials → get session cookies.

Navigate to booking link → extract form fields.

Submit booking form.

Parse result → send success/failure notification.

Update state.

2.4 Stealth Implementation
Each site gets its own HTTP client with:

Custom Transport that adds headers per request.

CookieJar (default net/http/cookiejar).

Custom RoundTripper to log requests and add jitter delays (optional).

Headers mimic a real browser:

text
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 ...
Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,...
Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.9
Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate, br
Connection: keep-alive
Referer: <base_url>
Add random delays (jitter) before sending the request using time.Sleep.

2.5 Error Handling & Retries
Retry transient errors (timeout, 5xx) with exponential backoff.

Max retries configurable.

Log all failures.
